SIMPLE: pedrail
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pedrail
<hw>Ped"rail`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Pedi-</er>;
<er>Rail</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A device
intended to replace the wheel of a self-propelled vehicle for use on
rough roads and to approximate to the smoothness in running of a wheel
on a metal track. The tread consists of a number of rubber shod feet
which are connected by ball-and-socket joints to the ends of sliding
spokes. Each spoke has attached to it a small roller which in its turn
runs under a short pivoted rail controlled by a powerful set of springs.
This arrangement permits the feet to accommodate themselves to obstacles
even such as steps or stairs. The pedrail was invented by one <person>B.
J. Diplock</person> of London, Eng.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A vehicle,
as a traction engine, having such pedrails.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pedregal</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
